Negatron...looks like it's time to delve back into cosmology.  Thanks.<br>
<br>
L2 vs some other folks:<br>
<br>
1) Egoism is not a mental disorder, at least not the last time I checked my DSM-3R (which admittedly has been awhile).  Narcissism is (perhaps was) classed as a personality disorder but isn't what we're speaking of here.  You might view it as socially counterproductive, but that doesn't make it a mental disorder.  Your dictionary definition presented only a building block of a larger belief system (such as satanism or objectivism).<br>
<br>
2) I think there's a need here to define terms, especially what qualifies as &quot;manipulation.&quot;  L2 seems to be using one definition, in which manipulation comprises extreme acts including the betrayal of even one's closest friends and relatives.  Treist et al seem to have a more narrow definition, in which manipulation comprises everday acts familiar to most of us plus others which may or may not extend into L2's range of the definition.  I haven't noticed them deny too much either, though.<br>
<br>
2a) Is there such a thing as true altruism?  Treist and Flex (and my flatmate) would say no, I think, while L2 would probably say yes.  My view is that altruism needs to be redefined.<br>
<br>
3) I think there's plenty of room for debate or discussion of the satanic/egoistic viewpoint without resorting to name calling rants.  L2, your perception of their belief system (which I'm not yet ready to equate to an accurate representation of what believe) may repel you, but I think you owe it to your open mind to ask questions rather than make assumptions and insult.  Such a question might be something like, &quot;Do you believe it is right and &quot;good&quot; to use your spouse/close friend in a way that brings you wealth while decreases theirs?&quot;  <br>
<br>
4) Knowing all kinds off people doesn't make you open-minded.  Accepting them does. (Well, not exactly, but I don't have time to expound so just hope you all get my drift).<br>
<br>
I would have to know much more of Treist/Flex's philosphy(ies) before rendering any kind of judgement.  That judgement would, of course, be based on my own beliefs, not some kind of illusory objective moral standard (ooohhh moral relativism vs objectivism, we haven't gone *there* yet!).  From what I see it isn't a very useful philosophy since it is centered (as I understand it) entirely on the practitioner; my preference is for a belief system that has a positive effect on society at large.  I think I could show that an egoistic belief system is ultimately self defeating rather than self enhancing, but more would have to be known and I'd need more time than I have for it.<br>
<br>
L2, your belief system is best served via calm, rational discussion.  Trust me on this.<br>
