</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/uclanmcstump.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ClanMcStump</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elite Poster</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(12/6/01 10:37:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=624.topic&index=118>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: .</span><hr size=1> Well, L2, the difference is in the definition.  First, since when we are talking about the belief of Egoism, I discounted any other definitions.  Granted, other defitions of egoism are :<br>
     2) Excessive preoccupation with one's own well-being and interests, usually accompanied by an inflated sense of self-importance<br>
     3)Egotism; conceit<br>
<br>
But since we are discussing religion and beliefs, the first definition is the only one that is really applicable :<br>
     1a)The ethical doctrine that morality has its foundations in self-interest. <br>
     1b)The ethical belief that self-interest is the just and proper motive for all human conduct<br>
<br>
In the case of definitions 2 and 3, egoism could be considered a synonym of the first defintion of narcissism:<br>
     1)Excessive love or admiration of oneself. See Synonyms at conceit<br>
<br>
The disorder you spoke of is called Narcissistic Personality Disorder (this is the name given to the disorder in the DSM-IV-TR).  Since I obtained the above defintions from dictionary.com I'll use the same for the disorder:<br>
     2)A psychological condition characterized by self-preoccupation, lack of empathy, and unconscious deficits in self-esteem<br>
<br>
Thats a pretty lousy definition, but so is the one i found in the on-line medical dictionary under Narcissistic Personality Disorder:<br>
     1)An individual with an inflated sense of self-importance<br>
<br>
Your point, as I understood it, was that the philosophy of Egoism and the mental disorder are one and the same so I am going to point out some differences based solely on definition.<br>
<br>
Egoism is the belief that self-interest is the underlying foundation of all morality.  This means that to an Egoist, all actions, whether they appear to be altruisticly motivated or not, are actually driven by your own wants and desires.  So a person who desires to help others may join the Peace Corp and go on to help thousands of people, but he did so only because it was something he *wanted* to do.<br>
<br>
A narcissistic personality focuses completely on itself, and cares little to nothing for the needs or desires for anyone else.<br>
<br>
So a believer of Egoism may help other people and have friends and lovers and truely care for those people.  But they do so believing that those feelings are self-serving.  On the other hand, a narcissist would rarely if ever really care about anyone other than himself because he feels that he is the only person worth such feelings.<br>
<br>
/sigh<br>
Talking about this is bringing back some memories of my work in the hospital.  Narcissists are... well, they're a tough person to care for.<br>
<br>
As for Egoists... well, its not a philosophy I agree with, but they make for some interesting conversationalists, thats for sure.<br>
